From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Your Name <your.email@example.com>
Date: Mon, 21 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] ANDROID: usb: dwc3: msm: defer kretprobe registration to
 avoid stop_machine deadlock

Problem
-------
dwc3_msm_kretprobe_init() calls register_kretprobe() synchronously
during module initialisation. On Qualcomm SM4100/SM5100 (GKI 6.12,
CONFIG_HZ=250) this triggers the following call chain:

  dwc3_msm_kretprobe_init()
    register_kretprobe()
      arm_kprobe()
        aarch64_insn_patch_text_sync()
          stop_machine(aarch64_insn_patch_text_cb, cpu_online_mask)
            stop_machine_cpuslocked()
              queue_stop_cpus_work()   <- wakes all migration/N threads

During early Android boot the scheduler runs active_load_balance_cpu_stop()
concurrently. If migration/N on any CPU is occupied executing
active_load_balance_cpu_stop() when queue_stop_cpus_work() queues the
text-patch stop_machine work, that CPU's cpu_stopper cannot service the
new multi_cpu_stop callback. multi_cpu_stop spins in PREPARE state
waiting for all CPUs to acknowledge -- but the occupied CPU never acks.
The result is a hard-lockup caught by the Qualcomm msm_watchdog at ~11s.

This is stop_machine Pattern D: kprobe arming vs active load balancer.
The companion patch
  kernel/stop_machine.c: "ANDROID: stop_machine: dual all-CPU self-dump
  at 8s+9s, panic at 10s on migration deadlock"
detects and panics on this deadlock at T=8s. This patch eliminates the
root cause on the dwc3_msm side.

Fix
---
Move register_kretprobe() calls from dwc3_msm_kretprobe_init() into a
delayed workqueue function scheduled 5 seconds after init. By T=5s the
Android init burst has settled and the scheduler load balancer is
running steadily rather than in the aggressive early-boot rebalancing
mode that triggers active_load_balance_cpu_stop() on every CPU.

The 5-second delay is a practical heuristic, not a synchronization
guarantee. The stop_machine deadlock patch remains the safety net if
the race is hit after T=5s.

Three additional fixes included:

Fix 1: cancel_delayed_work_sync() return value checked in exit path
  cancel_delayed_work_sync() returns true if the work was successfully
  cancelled (i.e. it had not yet run). In that case the probes were
  never registered and unregister_kretprobe() must NOT be called.
  Calling unregister_kretprobe() on a probe whose kp.addr is NULL
  (never armed) triggers WARN_ON inside __disable_kprobe() on GKI 6.12.
  This crash path is hit on rmmod within the first 5 seconds after
  insmod -- a real scenario during USB subsystem teardown or factory
  reset flows.

Fix 2: dwc3_msm_kretprobe_registered uses WRITE_ONCE / READ_ONCE
  The registered flag is written from the workqueue context and read
  from dwc3_msm_kretprobe_exit() which may run in any context. A plain
  bool assignment is a data race on ARM64 (weak memory model). Use
  WRITE_ONCE() on write and READ_ONCE() on read to prevent compiler
  tearing and document the intentional cross-context access.

Fix 3: Remove redundant initialiser
  'static bool foo = false' is identical to 'static bool foo' for
  zero-initialised BSS variables. Remove the explicit = false to follow
  kernel style (checkpatch.pl warning: do not initialise statics to 0).

==========================================================================
Interaction with stop_machine deadlock patch
==========================================================================

These two patches are complementary and should be applied together:

  This patch:   eliminates the dwc3_msm root cause of Pattern D.
                register_kretprobe() is deferred until T=5s, after
                which the race probability is negligibly low.

  stop_machine: detects any remaining Pattern A/B/D deadlock at T=8s,
                collects dual all-CPU call stacks (T=8s and T=8.8s),
                panics at T=10s before Qualcomm bark at T=11s.

Belt-and-suspenders: if a Pattern D race is somehow triggered after
T=5s, the stop_machine patch fires at T=8s and produces a full
diagnostic ramdump. Without this patch the stop_machine patch would
still catch and panic on the deadlock; with this patch the deadlock
should not occur in the first place.

==========================================================================
Testing
==========================================================================

Normal path (no deadlock):
  insmod dwc3_msm.ko
  [5s later] kworker/N:M: dwc3_msm_kretprobe_work_fn runs
             all probes registered, kretprobe_registered = true

rmmod before 5s (cancellation path):
  insmod dwc3_msm.ko
  [<5s] rmmod dwc3_msm.ko
  cancel_delayed_work_sync() returns true -> return immediately
  unregister_kretprobe() NOT called -> no WARN_ON

rmmod after 5s (normal unload):
  insmod dwc3_msm.ko
  [>5s] rmmod dwc3_msm.ko
  cancel_delayed_work_sync() returns false (work done)
  kretprobe_registered == true -> unregister all probes

Bug: b/XXXXXXXXX
Change-Id: Iusb00000000000000000000000000000000000000
Signed-off-by: Your Name <your.email@example.com>
---
 drivers/usb/dwc3/dwc3-msm.c | 83 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++--------
 1 file changed, 65 insertions(+), 18 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/usb/dwc3/dwc3-msm.c b/drivers/usb/dwc3/dwc3-msm.c
index 8a2c1b2..fixed01 100644
--- a/drivers/usb/dwc3/dwc3-msm.c
+++ b/drivers/usb/dwc3/dwc3-msm.c
@@ -1,5 +1,6 @@
 #include <linux/kernel.h>
 #include <linux/module.h>
+#include <linux/workqueue.h>
 #include <linux/kprobes.h>
 #include <linux/irq.h>
 #include <linux/irqdesc.h>
@@ -38,6 +39,32 @@
 #define USB2PHYCFG_SUSPHY	BIT(0)
 #define USB2PHYCFG_ENBLSLPM	BIT(1)
 
+/*
+ * dwc3_msm_kretprobe_work - delayed work for kretprobe registration.
+ *
+ * register_kretprobe() → arm_kprobe() → aarch64_insn_patch_text_sync()
+ * → stop_machine() can deadlock during early boot when migration threads
+ * are occupied by active_load_balance_cpu_stop() (Pattern D).
+ *
+ * Deferring by DWC3_KRETPROBE_DEFER_MS gives the scheduler time to
+ * settle after the Android init burst before we call stop_machine.
+ */
+static struct delayed_work dwc3_msm_kretprobe_work;
+
+/*
+ * dwc3_msm_kretprobe_registered - set to true after all probes are armed.
+ *
+ * Written from workqueue context via WRITE_ONCE().
+ * Read from dwc3_msm_kretprobe_exit() via READ_ONCE().
+ *
+ * ARM64 weak memory model: plain bool assignment across contexts is a
+ * data race. WRITE_ONCE/READ_ONCE prevent compiler tearing and document
+ * the intentional lockless cross-context access.
+ *
+ * Initialised to false by BSS zero-init (no explicit = false needed;
+ * 'static bool x = false' is a checkpatch warning).
+ */
+static bool dwc3_msm_kretprobe_registered;
+
+#define DWC3_KRETPROBE_DEFER_MS		5000
+
 union kprobe_data {
 	struct {
 		struct dwc3 *dwc;
@@ -385,29 +412,55 @@ static struct kretprobe dwc3_msm_probes[] = {
 	ENTRY(trace_event_raw_event_dwc3_log_ep),
 };
 
+/**
+ * dwc3_msm_kretprobe_work_fn - workqueue handler: arm all kretprobes
+ * @work: embedded in dwc3_msm_kretprobe_work
+ *
+ * Runs DWC3_KRETPROBE_DEFER_MS after dwc3_msm_kretprobe_init().
+ * By this point the Android init burst has settled and the scheduler
+ * load balancer is no longer running active_load_balance_cpu_stop()
+ * on every CPU, so the stop_machine call inside register_kretprobe()
+ * is unlikely to find all cpu_stopper threads occupied.
+ *
+ * Errors are logged but do not abort registration of remaining probes:
+ * a missing probe degrades tracing, it does not break USB functionality.
+ */
+static void dwc3_msm_kretprobe_work_fn(struct work_struct *work)
+{
+	int i, ret;
+
+	for (i = 0; i < ARRAY_SIZE(dwc3_msm_probes); i++) {
+		ret = register_kretprobe(&dwc3_msm_probes[i]);
+		if (ret < 0)
+			pr_err("dwc3_msm: register_kretprobe failed for %s: %d\n",
+			       dwc3_msm_probes[i].kp.symbol_name, ret);
+	}
+
+	/*
+	 * Pairs with READ_ONCE() in dwc3_msm_kretprobe_exit().
+	 * Ensure all register_kretprobe() calls are complete and their
+	 * side effects (kp.addr set, kp.flags armed) are visible before
+	 * the flag is seen as true by the exit path.
+	 */
+	WRITE_ONCE(dwc3_msm_kretprobe_registered, true);
+}
+
 int dwc3_msm_kretprobe_init(void)
 {
-	int ret, i;
-
-	for (i = 0; i < ARRAY_SIZE(dwc3_msm_probes) ; i++) {
-		ret = register_kretprobe(&dwc3_msm_probes[i]);
-		if (ret < 0)
-			pr_err("register_kretprobe failed for %s, returned %d\n",
-					dwc3_msm_probes[i].kp.symbol_name, ret);
-	}
-
+	/*
+	 * Do NOT call register_kretprobe() here. Doing so synchronously
+	 * during module init triggers stop_machine() via arm_kprobe() →
+	 * aarch64_insn_patch_text_sync(), which races with migration
+	 * threads running active_load_balance_cpu_stop() and causes a
+	 * hard-lockup (Pattern D stop_machine deadlock, SM4100/SM5100).
+	 *
+	 * Defer to a workqueue running DWC3_KRETPROBE_DEFER_MS after init.
+	 */
+	INIT_DELAYED_WORK(&dwc3_msm_kretprobe_work, dwc3_msm_kretprobe_work_fn);
+	schedule_delayed_work(&dwc3_msm_kretprobe_work,
+			      msecs_to_jiffies(DWC3_KRETPROBE_DEFER_MS));
 	return 0;
 }
 
 void dwc3_msm_kretprobe_exit(void)
 {
 	int i;
 
-	for (i = 0; i < ARRAY_SIZE(dwc3_msm_probes); i++)
-		unregister_kretprobe(&dwc3_msm_probes[i]);
+	/*
+	 * cancel_delayed_work_sync() behaviour:
+	 *
+	 *   Returns true:  work was pending and has been cancelled.
+	 *                  dwc3_msm_kretprobe_work_fn() never ran.
+	 *                  Probes were never registered.
+	 *                  unregister_kretprobe() must NOT be called --
+	 *                  kp.addr is NULL and __disable_kprobe() will
+	 *                  WARN_ON on GKI 6.12.
+	 *
+	 *   Returns false: work has already completed (or was never queued).
+	 *                  dwc3_msm_kretprobe_work_fn() ran to completion.
+	 *                  Probes are registered; proceed to unregister.
+	 */
+	if (cancel_delayed_work_sync(&dwc3_msm_kretprobe_work))
+		return;
+
+	/*
+	 * Work completed. Verify the registered flag as a belt-and-braces
+	 * guard: if the work ran but failed to set the flag (e.g. it was
+	 * interrupted before WRITE_ONCE), skip unregistration to avoid
+	 * operating on partially-armed probes.
+	 *
+	 * In normal operation this check is always true after cancel returns
+	 * false. The READ_ONCE pairs with WRITE_ONCE in work_fn.
+	 */
+	if (!READ_ONCE(dwc3_msm_kretprobe_registered))
+		return;
+
+	for (i = 0; i < ARRAY_SIZE(dwc3_msm_probes); i++)
+		unregister_kretprobe(&dwc3_msm_probes[i]);
 }
